00:37.180 --> 00:38.940
And here are your hosts.

00:43.520 --> 00:52.120
This is David Crews and Daryl Lane. One of the most honored and respected of
today's science fiction authors is the English writer Brian Aldiss. His first

00:52.120 --> 00:59.980
science fiction story was published in 1954, and since then he's won every award
the field has to offer, both in this country and throughout Europe. Aldiss is a

00:59.980 --> 01:07.680
craftsman of the highest order. The attention he gives to style, character, and
structure demonstrates the literary polish that often distinguishes British

01:07.680 --> 01:14.860
science fiction from American. He's written a few non-science fiction novels, in
fact, that have been bestsellers in England. We asked him why he chose to

01:14.860 --> 01:24.640
concentrate his career in science fiction rather than mainstream literature.
Well, I regard myself as a writer, and this difference that seems to be so

01:24.640 --> 01:36.500
apparent to other people is not so apparent to me. I'm interested in a kind of
literature of ideas, and sometimes that strays to one side of the science

01:36.500 --> 01:51.580
fiction fence and sometimes to another. But it's not as though one day I'm
riding a horse and the next day I'm riding a cow. It's just that I'm in the same

01:51.580 --> 02:04.180
vehicle all the time, but sometimes the identification marks change. That's the
way I see it. In some of his personal essays on science fiction, Aldiss tells of

02:04.180 --> 02:12.660
how he was introduced to the field as a child through lurid pulp magazines he
found at Woolworths. His family disapproved of his reading such literature, but

02:12.660 --> 02:22.320
Aldiss was fascinated and wouldn't give it up. He explains why he was so drawn to
science fiction at an early age. I believe it was really that I never had a firm

02:22.320 --> 02:33.780
conviction as a child that the world was as all the grown-ups claimed it to be.
It seemed to me that it was a much more interesting place than any of them

02:33.780 --> 02:46.260
believed, or that they sought to deny it was an interesting place at all. They
were all busy working in their shops and making their money and leading their

02:46.260 --> 03:05.500
routine lives. And I was a bit of a kind of escapologist, you see, when I was a
child. I picked up a phrase from an old cowboy movie where one of the wrestlers

03:05.500 --> 03:11.120
says out of the corner of his mouth, Let's go while the going's good.

03:34.020 --> 03:42.280
Aldiss's streak of wildness later led to unique experiments in some of his
science fiction novels. He gained a reputation as an innovator, as a science

03:42.280 --> 03:50.120
fiction author who wasn't afraid to introduce new styles and concepts into a
fairly traditional field. Two good examples of his innovative techniques were

03:50.120 --> 03:58.400
the novels Report on Probability A and Barefoot in the Head, published in the
late 60s. Their complex styles were avant-garde and confusing to many science

03:58.400 --> 04:07.640
fiction readers. We asked Aldiss if he deliberately sought to open up science
fiction or enlarge its boundaries with such experiments. Well, you understand

04:07.640 --> 04:21.880
that's not exactly a motive in writing to expand the field. I think what you
think you're doing at the time is trying to find a little... How shall we mix

04:21.880 --> 04:37.240
the metaphor? Trying to find a little breathing space where the ground isn't too
trampled already by the hordes of other writers. And so you seek out, I suppose,

04:37.920 --> 04:54.380
the perimeters of the field as it's currently defined. And in that way, if you
accidentally extend it well, that's very nice. And of course, some people are

04:54.380 --> 05:01.520
grateful to you and other people are very cross with you for doing it because
they say you're breaking the rules. Next time, we'll talk with Brian Aldiss about

05:01.520 --> 05:02.340
some of his works.

05:09.460 --> 05:17.540
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:17.540 --> 05:18.320
Odessa, Texas.

