06:28.220 --> 06:29.700
And here are your hosts.

06:34.320 --> 06:43.460
This is Daryl Lane. And David Crews. In 1973, Brian Aldiss published a book on the
origin and history of science fiction entitled Billion Year Spree. He gave us an

06:43.460 --> 06:52.600
interesting account of the reasons he wrote the book, including some comments on
one of his novels, Barefoot in the Head. Well, I'd written a novel called

06:52.600 --> 07:04.740
Barefoot in the Head, and it really didn't receive a very kind initial
attention, although the premise was simple enough. Barefoot in the Head was

07:04.740 --> 07:18.800
about the world stopped in its tracks by drugs. This was the late 60s, remember,
when the flower power people had been around and we had had all this love-in

07:18.800 --> 07:32.660
stuff. And towards the end of the 60s, the bills, as we say in England, the
checks were coming in for all that kind of stuff. And they were already finding

07:32.660 --> 07:43.120
the fetuses in the trash cans of Haight-Ashbury. So that Barefoot in the Head
was an ambivalent book written in a difficult language. But I poured into it all

07:43.120 --> 07:59.100
I knew about A, science fiction, and B, writing. And I was a little surprised at
the tepid response it got, the angry response it got, the anonymous letters. So

07:59.100 --> 08:09.540
I thought, well, let's be finished with the science fiction field. And I
thought, well, before I leave it, I ought to write down all that I know and love

08:09.540 --> 08:21.460
about it before I forget. And so really I settled down with that in mind, to
write Billion Year Spree, and also to have an argument as I raised my hat and

08:21.460 --> 08:35.900
left the science fictional community. But by the time I got to the end of the
thing, you know, three years had passed, and just writing the book turned me on

08:35.900 --> 08:45.040
to science fiction again. Billion Year Spree is full of Aldiss's personal but
fascinating ideas. One provocative idea, heresy to some science fiction fans,

08:45.220 --> 08:53.760
was that Hugo Gernsback, the father of modern science fiction, was a disastrous
influence on the field. We asked Aldiss what he meant by that. Well, as you

08:53.760 --> 09:03.600
probably know, that I did say something of that sort. And since then, people
have been threatening to break my legs and my arms and shoot me and hang me and

09:03.600 --> 09:21.140
kick me out of the science fiction field and all sorts of things like that. But
I guess that what I was worried about was the way science fiction was segregated

09:21.140 --> 09:38.020
by Gernsback into a magazine. So if you wanted to find science fiction, you had
to go to a magazine that had a name like Astounding or Amazing or Staggering,

09:38.180 --> 09:56.560
which had a huge three-dimensional title with rivets in it. And that resulted in
a monoculture. And we all know that there are dangers in monoculture. And I

09:56.560 --> 10:11.920
simply thought that science fiction would be better as an uncaged animal that
could rove at large where it would. But nowadays, people complain that science

10:11.920 --> 10:22.680
fiction is segregated and that people think you're funny if you read it and that
it has to have a special place in a bookshop right next to weirdo cult books

10:22.680 --> 10:34.240
about flying saucers or whatever. Well, my answer to that is that, yes, I agree.
I think that's too bad. I think science fiction is much better than that. But

10:34.240 --> 10:45.960
the reason why it is there is because of the segregation that was introduced by
Hugo Gernsback. That was my argument. Anyone seeking to gain a perspective on

10:45.960 --> 10:52.580
science fiction and fantasy should read Billion Year Spree, a personal but
fascinating account of the field by one of science fiction's true men of

10:52.580 --> 10:55.160
letters. Tomorrow more with Brian Aldiss.

11:02.460 --> 11:10.560
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

11:10.560 --> 11:14.680
Odessa, Texas. 

