12:21.680 --> 12:23.380
And here are your hosts.

12:28.440 --> 12:37.460
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. Brian Aldiss does unexpected but fascinating
things in his science fiction stories. Though Aldiss is often an innovator, he

12:37.460 --> 12:44.980
also understands and cherishes the traditions of science fiction. Aldiss has
demonstrated his fondness for science fiction's past by redoing some of its

12:44.980 --> 12:53.280
classic novels. An Island Called Moreau, for instance, was based on H.G. Wells'
The Island of Dr. Moreau. In his book, Frankenstein Unbound, drew on Mary

12:53.280 --> 13:01.640
Shelley's Frankenstein, published in 1818, which some call the first science
fiction novel. Aldiss relates the impulse behind his writing of Frankenstein

13:01.640 --> 13:18.060
Unbound. I think that I write about the things that fascinate me most. And I'm
kind of a literary man. And I certainly much admire Mary Shelley's Frankenstein.

13:18.060 --> 13:33.380
It's the most remarkable work for anyone, not least for a young lady not quite
touching 18. And when I had the impulse to write Frankenstein Unbound, it was

13:33.380 --> 13:48.300
really an exegetical impulse to draw everybody's attention, if possible, to the
excellence of that original novel, which, as you know, has been slandered and

13:48.300 --> 14:02.480
pilloried by the filmmakers who've seen nothing better in it than a stupid,
shambling, and inarticulate monster. I wanted to restore the monster to his true

14:02.480 --> 14:16.180
evil power as an articulate, feeling and maimed being worthy of our compassion
and perhaps our hatred.

14:17.820 --> 14:27.520
Aldiss says there was a true creative impulse behind Frankenstein Unbound. But
that wasn't so for An Island Called Moreau. I have to admit that later on I did

14:27.520 --> 14:42.660
the same thing with Wells' Island of Dr. Moreau. And that was, I believe, ill
-advised. It's one of the few novels I've written that didn't begin with some

14:42.660 --> 14:48.200
kind of genuine lust

14:48.200 --> 15:00.740
to create, will to create, with fire in my stomach. I just thought it was
something I could do. And that was too tiny a motive, I believe, for the book

15:00.740 --> 15:15.840
that I eventually turned out. But I don't believe that it supersedes or in any
way aids the Wells version. The funny thing is, I have to say, that that novel

15:15.840 --> 15:26.140
was extremely well received in this country and in Great Britain. Another Aldiss
tribute to science fiction's past is his novella, The Saliva Tree. It's a

15:26.140 --> 15:34.020
playful book, a clever tribute to H.G. Wells, who happens to be an unseen
character in it. It's about an invisible alien monster ravaging the countryside

15:34.020 --> 15:42.180
of late Victorian England. Invading monsters and invisibility are two of Wells'
themes, of course. And during the story, all of Wells' themes and the titles of

15:42.180 --> 15:49.700
his books are somehow worked in. The story's main character, Gregory Rolles, has
been writing letters to H.G. Wells about the happenings in the countryside.

15:50.520 --> 16:01.840
Wells comes to meet Rolles as the story ends. Well, in H.G. Wells, our central
character is about to relate to H.G. Wells the horrific events that have gone on

16:01.840 --> 16:22.640
down on the farm. and in those events are really the germs for all of Wells'
science fiction. I mean, you know, there's a kind of a joke on H.G. Wells there.

16:22.880 --> 16:35.240
I mean, we all owe a great debt to H.G. Wells because he preempted almost all of
the science fiction themes and so in a way The Saliva Tree is a kind of horrific

16:35.240 --> 16:46.800
joke to show that in fact Wells didn't have any original ideas. They were all
given to him by this guy who knocks on the door at the end of the story. More on

16:46.800 --> 16:48.480
the works of Brian Aldiss next time.

