18:19.300 --> 18:20.960
And here are your hosts.

18:25.380 --> 18:33.440
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews. English science fiction author Brian Aldiss
sometimes writes books which are difficult to categorize. Aldiss has written

18:33.440 --> 18:41.840
familiar science fiction, such as his first novel, which was published in this
country in 1959, as Starship. But many of his novels are experimental or avant

18:41.840 --> 18:51.440
-garde in both theme and structure. Report on Probability A, published in 1969,
is a good example of this type. A 1976 novel, though, the Malacia Tapestry, is

18:51.440 --> 18:59.380
one of his most unique novels, a strange but richly rewarding book. And it
completely resists categories. It could be called science fiction, but it's not

18:59.380 --> 19:12.160
quite that. Some might say it's fantasy, but it's not that either. Aldiss talks
about the inspiration behind the book. The model I had was a pictorial one.

19:12.300 --> 19:30.800
That's often the case... Well, in several of my novels, I start from a pictorial
beginning. And my pictorial beginnings with Malacia were the etchings which the

19:30.800 --> 19:47.880
Italian artist, the Baroque artist, GBT Epilo, made at the end of his life.
Towards the end of his life, he retired, and he started etching these mysterious

19:47.880 --> 19:52.920
little pictures of wizards,

19:53.960 --> 19:57.400
Mountebanks, soldiers,

19:58.920 --> 20:12.420
punchinellos, people being dug out of the ground from graves, owls, serpents
burning on altars, all sorts of mysterious symbols in these lovely little

20:12.420 --> 20:25.140
pictures. And no one's actually figured out what they're meant to be. It's like
a science fictional alternative world where magic rules, I suppose you'd say,

20:26.160 --> 20:38.260
and I suppose that was one of the things I liked about them. So I thought, well,
if no one else can reconstruct this world to their satisfaction, I'll have a go

20:38.260 --> 20:52.360
at it. And so I started writing short stories around the more haunting of these
etchings of Tiepolo's. Malacia itself is a grand city which exists in what

20:52.360 --> 21:00.400
appears to be an alternate universe suggestive of Earth's ancient past. There is
no technology to speak of, sorcery of a limited sort seems to work, and there

21:00.400 --> 21:08.180
are all manner of exotic creatures such as flying beings which resemble humans.
The novel's main concern is art, an unusual theme for a science fiction or

21:08.180 --> 21:15.520
fantasy book, seemingly more appropriate for a romantic poet. Aldiss told us
that the theme of art came out of a serious illness he had while writing the

21:15.520 --> 21:21.680
book. The effect of this internal complaint I had, this hepatitis,

21:25.380 --> 21:37.300
made me feel that, well, my lifespan was limited, and I'd frolicked about a good
deal and had written some books that I perhaps didn't take as seriously as I

21:37.300 --> 21:52.540
should do, and that what I dearly loved was writing, and that I wanted to make a
statement about art. And really, Malacia is, it's all about art from the title

21:52.540 --> 22:11.920
onwards. If the book has a power, it is the power of meditations on the nature
of art, which is at once to transfigure and at the same time to petrify. And as

22:11.920 --> 22:28.420
you know, Malacia itself is a city-state under a curse of zero change. Well,
that's like a work of art. It's like Tiepolo's little etchings. They may be

22:28.420 --> 22:38.800
forever enigmatic to us, but they're forever unchanging. The Malacia Tapestry,
by one of the masters of modern science fiction. A difficult novel to

22:38.800 --> 22:43.300
categorize, but a fascinating one to read. More with author Brian Aldiss on our
next show.

