24:10.560 --> 24:12.180
And here are your hosts.

24:16.980 --> 24:25.420
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. Brian Aldiss' latest science fiction novel is
the masterful achievement of an author who is at the height of his very awesome

24:25.420 --> 24:33.740
powers. It's called Helliconia Spring, and it's the first volume of a trilogy
about an Earth-like planet called Helliconia. Aldiss tells us about the planet and

24:33.740 --> 24:52.400
the books. Helliconia is the name of a planet that's really much like Earth, and
a lot of Earth-like things go on there. But it is the child of binary suns, and

24:52.400 --> 25:02.140
it takes two and a half thousand years to go around the primary. I mean two and
a half thousand Earth years.

25:04.940 --> 25:19.640
Which is to say that between one winter and the next, you can have a whole lot
of civilizations doing a whole lot of declining and falling. And of course,

25:19.900 --> 25:38.420
falling and rising. And so that these three long volumes really just cover parts
of one of Helliconia's great years. So there's at once this marvelous continuity,

25:38.420 --> 25:53.080
as I see it, of one year, and yet of many generations and many cultures. And
that's the basic plan of the book. They're simply titled. The first one's

25:53.080 --> 26:04.920
Helliconia Spring. That's the one that's out. The one I'm writing is Helliconia
Summer. And after that, I go on to Helliconia Winter. After centuries of a

26:04.920 --> 26:12.820
deadening winter, spring is coming to Helliconia. And the primitive men of the
planet are waking up to the greater possibilities of life. To higher aspirations

26:12.820 --> 26:22.200
and knowledge. To the construction of a new civilization. The first volume
traces the life of a nomadic hunter named Yuli and his descendants. Because the

26:22.200 --> 26:36.380
first volume's about the sun bursting out. The first volume is just stacked full
of things bursting out. And people bursting out. Animals bursting out. It's a

26:36.380 --> 26:37.700
great bursting out novel.

26:45.660 --> 26:53.840
Circling Helliconia is a satellite from Earth. A huge observation station which
monitors everything that happens in Helliconia and beams it to Earth. Aldiss

26:53.840 --> 27:06.140
spent a painstaking four years on the book, striving for accuracy and realism.
Well, I hope people will find that it's full of reality. That's why I say the

27:06.140 --> 27:21.880
moral of it should be mere existence. Because I think they'll recognize their
own lives passing through the book. And the other motive I had was that I grew

27:21.880 --> 27:38.800
rather alarmed at the way so much science fiction, since it's become more
popular, has been full of, what shall we say, fantasy, wish fulfillment. I

27:38.800 --> 27:56.800
didn't like that. I think that science fiction should reflect the facts of life.
The hard facts of life. It shouldn't just be some nonsense about one guy against

27:56.800 --> 28:09.620
a malign empire who goes out and, you know, kills the chief baddie. I thought it
should have a little more contact for reality. And moreover, I'll sound old

28:09.620 --> 28:22.180
-fashioned if I say this, but I think that sort of thing is better for the
nation's youth than the old hogwash about telepathic dragons and all the rest of

28:22.180 --> 28:22.400
it.

28:29.660 --> 28:36.600
Helliconia Spring is a remarkable and unique achievement by a man who is not just
a great science fiction writer, but one of the finest writers of our time.

